04196nam a22005295i 9780300146196DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20181996ctu    fo  d z      eng d  a97803001461967 a10.12987/97803001461962doi  a(DE-B1597)486806  a(OCoLC)861792546  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  actucUS-CT 7aHIS0000002bisacsh1 aBarron, Patrick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aAmerican Elites /cPatrick Barron, Rachael Diprose, Michael Woolcock. 1aNew Haven, CT : bYale University Press, c[2018] 4c©1996  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPREFACE -- tOne.. The Few Versus the Many: Competing Views Regarding the Structure of Power -- tTwo Room at the Top: Issues of Social Class, Education, and Access to Power -- tThree. The Structure of Ideology -- tFour. Four Dimensions of Ideology and Their Impact -- tFive. The Components of Collectivist Liberalism -- tSix. Expressive Individualism, Religion, and the Family -- tSeven. Components of the Adversary Culture -- tEight. Personality, Family, and Ideology -- tNine. Conclusion: Divided Elites, American Society, and Social Change -- tAppendix: The Interview Sample and Questionnaire -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis detailed and fascinating portrait of America's elite leaders is based on interviews with more than 1800 members of ten strategic leadership groups—including federal judges, business executives, religious leaders, high-level bureaucrats, military leaders, labor union chiefs, lawyers, leading journalists, and motion picture and television magnates. The results of the survey—the most comprehensive ever conducted on America's elite groups—enable the authors to examine and analyze elite groups' structure and current social and political tensions in American society. The authors begin by examining elite theory in political science and sociology. Rejecting power elite, ruling class, and "new class' theories, they propose the concept of competing "strategic elites" as the most accurate characterization of the structure of power in the U.S. Their study compares the backgrounds, ideological differences, and predominant personality characteristics of members of the different elite groups and reveals that leadership groups in the U.S. are sharply divided in complex ways on various issues. Catholic religious leaders, for example, are quite liberal on economic issues but very conservative on cultural issues while the Hollywood elite is moderate on economic issues, quite liberal on cultural issues, and much more alienated from American society than are members of other leadership groups.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh1 aDiprose, Rachael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWoolcock, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000z97831105380140 cprintz978030006534340uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030014619640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300146196423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300146196/original  a978-3-11-053801-4  Yale University Press eBook-Package Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY